    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but we already do scan verification for transfers. We've tightened up the picking and put-away protocols a lot over the last few months, and we're still seeing these gaps. It feels almost irrational, like the inventory is just being disrupted by some unseen factor that doesn't follow the usual error patterns. \n\nIf the technical and manual processes are all verified and correct, what are the more \"unconventional\" or non-obvious causes logistics managers usually look at when they can't find a logical paper trail for small losses?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the system and processes seem flawless, you start looking at the environment and the people. Unconventional causes often involve small, systemic issues like improper storage conditions leading to component degradation, or slight variations in how different shifts perform tasks. Sometimes, it's a subtle issue with the equipment, like miscalibrated scanners or faulty conveyor weights causing small, undocumented movements. You might need to review the physical layout and the environment itself.",
      "source": "target",
